r}{\textless}/span{\textgreater}mm), Southern Andes (14.4{\textless}span class="thinspace"{\textgreater}{\textless}/span{\textgreater}$\pm${\textless}span class="thinspace"{\textgreater}{\textless}/span{\textgreater}0.1{\textless}span class="thinspace"{\textgreater}{\textless}/span{\textgreater}mm) and Svalbard (17.0{\textless}span class="thinspace"{\textgreater}{\textless}/span{\textgreater}$\pm${\textless}span class="thinspace"{\textgreater}{\textless}/span{\textgreater}4.6{\textless}span class="thinspace"{\textgreater}{\textless}/span{\textgreater}mm). Including parametric uncertainty in the calibrated mass balance parameters, gives an upper bound global volume loss of 247.3{\textless}span class="thinspace"{\textgreater}{\textless}/span{\textgreater}mm, sea-level equivalent by the end of the century. Such large ice losses will have inevitable consequences for sea-level rise and for water supply in glacier-fed river systems.{\textless}/p{\textgreater}},
	Author = {Shannon, Sarah and Smith, Robin and Wiltshire, Andy and Payne, Tony and Huss, Matthias and Betts, Richard and Caesar, John and Koutroulis, Aris and Jones, Darren and Harrison, Stephan},
